        <div xml:id="KT170-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">varaiviṭai āṟṟāḷ eṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ kūṟiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the confidante who was anxious that she would not have the strength [to await] the time of marriage.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT170">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                palaruṅ kūṟukavaḵ taṟiyā tōrē</l>
<l>                yaruvi tanta nāṭkura leruvai</l>
<l>                kayanā ṭiyāṉai kavaḷa māntu</l>
<l>                malaikeḻu nāṭaṉ kēṇmai</l>
<l>                talaipō kāmainaṟ kaṟintaṉeṉ yāṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>May all the many talk who don't know that:</l>
           <l>I have well understood the limitlessness</l>
           <l rend="indent">of the intimacy with the man from the mountainous land,</l>
           <l rend="indent">where the elephant searching the pond feeds, [like] on rice balls,<note place="foot">Or, with the tradition: "... where the elephant (normally) feeds on rice-balls, (but now) searches the pond for Eruvai plants ...". (Cf. PN 101.7, 114.3, 337.14).</note></l>
           <l rend="indent">on the reed<note place="foot">What might eruvai be (not included in the DED)? And what is meant by the specification <term xml:lang="ta">aruvi tanta nāḷ</term>? What is expressed by the image? HE will return to HER, just as the elephant gets enough of the eruvai found by chance and comes back to his usual <term xml:lang="ta">kavaḷam</term>?</note> in fresh(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nāḷ</term> is somewhat strange here. TVG reads it as "in the early morning", but that seems quite arbitrary.</note> bunches given by the waterfall.</l>


            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
